pes on req or return\n     export function handleRequest(req) {\n     // Line 39 -- no type on payload\n     function processUser(payload): unknown {\n     // Line 51 -- no type on data\n     function validate(data) {\n     ```\n\n5. Finding 5: Braceless if-statement violates project always-braces rule\n   - File: `review-src/handler.ts:21`\n   - Severity (initial): Suggestion\n   - Description: The admin dispatch guard is a single-statement if with no braces. Project CLAUDE.md mandates: \"Never write braceless one-liners. Every `if`, ... must use `{ }` blocks, even for single statements.\" A future editor adding a second line to this branch would silently exclude it from the conditional.\n   - Code context:\n     ```ts\n     if (payload.admin === true) return processAdmin(payload);\n     ```\n\n## Project Guidelines\n\nFrom the project's CLAUDE.md (global rules, authoritative):\n- \"Always use braces for control flow bodies: Never write braceless one-liners. Every `if`, `else`, `else if`, `for`, `while`, and each `case`/`default` body in a `switch` must use `{ }` blocks, even for single statements.\"\n- \"Blank lines around control flow and returns: Insert a blank line before and after `if`, `else`, `switch`, `for`, `while`, `try`, `catch`, `finally`, and `return` statements.\"\n\n## Full File for Reference\n\n```ts\n// review-src/handler.ts\ninterface RawRequest {\n  body: string;\n  headers: Record<string, string>;\n}\n\nexport function handleRequest(req) {\n  const payload = JSON.parse(req.body);\n\n  if (payload.admin === true) return processAdmin(payload);\n\n  const result = processUser(payload);\n\n  let notified = false;\n  if (notified) {\n    sendAuditLog(payload);\n  }\n\n  return result;\n}\n\nfunction processAdmin(payload: RawRequest): unknown {\n  return { role: 'admin', data: payload };\n}\n\nfunction processUser(payload): unknown {\n  try {\n    return validate(payload);\n  } catch (e) {\n    return null;\n  }\n}\n\nfunction validate(data) {\n  const name = data.name.trim();\n  return { ok: true, name };\n}\n\nfunction sendAuditLog(payload: RawRequest): void {\n  // TODO: wire the audit sink.\n}\n```\n\n## Request\n\nValidate these 5 findings. Confirm or reject each. Identify any cross-cutting patterns or additional issues I missed. Confirm or revise my initial severity assignments.","agentId":"a564ad3bd49d27f0f","agentType":"lz-advisor:reviewer","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All five findings confirmed against the file. Line numbers match. Note `processAdmin` (line 35) annotates `payload: RawRequest` but receives the parsed JSON, not the wire request -- a type-correctness issue the executor did not flag.\n\n### Critical\n\n1. review-src/handler.ts:17: `JSON.parse(req.body)` unguarded at trust boundary; malformed/empty body throws `SyntaxError` that crashes handler. Wrap in try/catch returning a 400-shaped error.\n\n### Important\n\n2. review-src/handler.ts:52: `data.name.trim()` derefs `name` with no guard; missing/non-string `name` throws `TypeError`. Guard `typeof data?.name === 'string'`.\n3. review-src/handler.ts:44-45: catch swallows error; `return null` hides validation failure from caller. Log `e`, or rethrow a typed error.\n4. review-src/handler.ts:27-30: `notified` never set true; audit branch is dead. Set `notified` on the real condition, or remove the flag.\n5. review-src/handler.ts:13,39,51: `req`/`payload`/`data` implicit `any`; boundary untyped. Annotate `req: RawRequest` and return types; type helpers.\n\n### Suggestions\n\n6. review-src/handler.ts:21: braceless `if` violates project always-braces rule. Add `{ }` block around `return processAdmin(payload)`.\n\n### Questions\n\n7. review-src/handler.ts:35: `processAdmin` types `payload` as `RawRequest`, but it receives the parsed JSON, not the wire request. Is `RawRequest` the wrong type here?\n\n### Per-finding validation\n\nValidation of Finding 7: `payload` is `JSON.parse(req.body)` output (line 17) -- arbitrary parsed JSON, not the `{body, headers}` wire object `RawRequest` describes. `processAdmin` (line 35) and `sendAuditLog` (line 57) both annotate it `RawRequest`, so the annotation is structurally wrong unless the body always deserializes to a `RawRequest` shape. The binary: is `RawRequest` mislabeled for parsed payloads, or is the parse-vs-wire distinction intentional?\n\n### Cross-Cutting Patterns\n\nFindings 1, 2, and 5 share one root cause: no validated schema at the boundary. Untyped `req` (5) lets the unguarded parse (1) feed an unshaped `payload` into `validate`, where the unguarded deref (2) throws. That throw is then swallowed by the finding-3 catch (review-src/handler.ts:44), so a malformed request returns success-shaped `null` rather than crashing visibly -- 1, 2, and 3 compound into silent data corruption, not a clean failure. A single parse-and-validate step (zod/typed guard) at line 17 collapses 1, 2, 5, and Finding 7's type mismatch. Findings 4 (dead branch) and 6 (braces) are independent.\n\n### Missed surfaces (optional)\n\n`sendAuditLog` (line 57) is a no-op stub; even if Finding 4's dead branch were fixed, audit logging would silently do nothing -- worth a tracking issue."}],"totalDurationMs":18432,"totalTokens":33757,"totalToolUseCount":1,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1075,"cache_read_input_tokens":31599,"output_tokens":1081,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1075},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"toolStats":{"readCount":1,"searchCount":0,"bashCount":0,"editFileCount":0,"linesAdded":0,"linesRemoved":0,"otherToolCount":0}}}
